<Author>saramwrap
<Content>Lovely building, lousy hotel The Hilton St. Charles is the newest Hilton property in New Orleans... but you wouldn't know it from a visit. Located in a renovated historic building a few blocks from the French Quarter, the lobby does boast impressive marble walls and brass-decorated elevators. But don't get used to this level of opulence.The double room we booked for a business trip was decent in size, but already looked well-worn less than a year after the hotel's opening. The floors were uneven, the tub was dingy, and the light switch in the bathroom wouldn't always stay on. The room was reasonably clean, though we found an odd assortment of towels (no bath towels, too many bathmats) at check-in and struggled with housekeeping to correct this issue. We also had a long wait (almost an hour) for the delivery of toilet paper after a request was made. The hotel's biggest disappointment is in the Executive Lounge. As a Hilton Gold member, I have visited many properties and enjoyed the exclusive lounge offered for frequent travelers. I look forward to continental breakfasts, concierge services, happy hours, snacks, and a place to relax. The Hilton St. Charles has an open nook that serves as the lounge, which is unadvertised on hotel signs and not adequately staffed or stocked. The boasted Skyview Terrace was continuously closed during our stay, and hotel signs listed it on a different floor than it actually exists.At check-out, I reported my experience to hotel staff, and they seemed genuinely surprised. I hope that this new property improves its offerings, and brings it up to the standards expected of a Hilton. 
